## 12. Space-drop

Balls rain, tilt to catch.

```scheme
(define g-x 0)
(define (space-drop)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/floor! 240)
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     (when (input/down? 'left)  (set! g-x (- g-x 0.05)))
     (when (input/down? 'right) (set! g-x (+ g-x 0.05)))
     (world/gravity! g-x 0.4)
     (when (= (modulo (world/frame) 15) 0)
       (let ((b (world/spawn 'ball
                             (+ 30 (modulo (world/hash) 260)) 10)))
         (entity/shape! b 'circle 5)
         (entity/bounce! b 0.5)))
     (world/step)
     (paint-clear)
     (world/each 'ball
                 (lambda (b) (paint-cell 'ball (entity/x b) (entity/y b) 5 5)))
     (paint-text (string-append \"Tilt: \" (number->string g-x)) 10 10))))
(big-bang space-drop)
```

---

Twelve games. Read one per morning. Mutate one per afternoon. Ship
your own variant per week. That is a year of games from this appendix
alone.

Every game uses only verbs from the reference. Every game runs. Every
game is one screen. Every game teaches ONE thing.

---

## Move-and-stop compositions — 6 micro-games (added 2026-07-18)

The twelve games above teach one thing each. This next set teaches
**compositional constraint** — how to hold TWO game rules at once
(move AND stop, spawn AND despawn, animate AND halt). Each example
below is under 30 lines and uses only CORE verbs.

The pattern is uniform: name each constraint, pick the verb for
each, compose them in `on-frame`, verify each constraint independently.

### 13. Move right, stop at edge

Sprite moves right at a constant velocity, then stops when its x
coordinate reaches the right edge of the world.

```scheme
(define (move-stop-right)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 20 120))
        (right-edge 300))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 12)
    (entity/set-vel! p 2 0)         ;; constraint 1: moving right
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (world/step)
       (when (>= (entity/x p) right-edge)   ;; constraint 2: stop at edge
         (entity/set-vel! p 0 0))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 12)))))
(big-bang move-stop-right)
```

Two constraints, held together every frame. Constraint 1: keep
moving. Constraint 2: if we've reached the edge, stop. Both are
checked every tick. Neither drifts.

### 14. Move while key held, stop when released

Sprite moves right ONLY while the right arrow key is held. Releasing
stops it. Uses `input/down?` for held-key detection.

```scheme
(define (move-while-held)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 12)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (cond
         ((input/down? 'right) (entity/set-vel! p 3 0))   ;; constraint 1: right held
         ((input/down? 'left)  (entity/set-vel! p -3 0))  ;; also left held
         (else                 (entity/set-vel! p 0 0)))  ;; constraint 2: none held → stop
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 12)))))
(big-bang move-while-held)
```

The `cond` holds both constraints. If a directional key is down, set
matching velocity. If no key is down (else), zero the velocity. The
sprite stops the frame you release the key.

### 15. Ball rolls, hits wall, stops

Ball starts with velocity, gravity pulls it down, and the world
floor stops its fall. Uses `world/floor!` for the stop-condition.

```scheme
(define (roll-and-stop)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.4)
  (world/floor! 220)                       ;; constraint 2: stop at floor
  (let ((b (world/spawn 'ball 30 30)))
    (entity/shape! b 'circle 6)
    (entity/bounce! b 0)                    ;; no bounce; hits and stops
    (entity/set-vel! b 3 0)                 ;; constraint 1: rolling right
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ball (entity/x b) (entity/y b) 6 6)))))
(big-bang roll-and-stop)
```

Gravity pulls it down. Rightward velocity moves it sideways. The
floor at y=220 stops downward motion. Bounce coefficient of 0 means
it does not rebound. Two-axis constraint composition, three verbs.

### 16. Thrust and drift, stop when button released

Ship thrusts forward while a button is held; releasing does NOT
instantly stop it (thrust decays through drag). Introduces
`entity/drag!` as the natural decay verb.

```scheme
(define (thrust-drift-stop)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((s (world/spawn 'ship 20 120)))
    (entity/shape! s 'triangle 8)
    (entity/drag! s 0.02)                    ;; constraint 3: friction slows drift
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'a)                ;; constraint 1: thrust while held
         (let ((vx (car (entity/vel s))))
           (entity/set-vel! s (+ vx 0.15) (cadr (entity/vel s)))))
       ;; constraint 2: no explicit stop — drag brings velocity to zero
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x s) (entity/y s) 8 8)))))
(big-bang thrust-drift-stop)
```

Three constraints layered. Hold 'a' to accelerate. Release and drag
gradually reduces velocity toward zero. No hard-stop — the physics
itself is the halting mechanism.

### 17. Glide to click, stop when arrived

Player character moves smoothly toward a target point set by mouse
click, and stops when it arrives. Uses `motion/move-to` and a
distance check.

```scheme
(define target-x 160)
(define target-y 120)
(define (glide-to-target)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'hero 20 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 12)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)              ;; constraint 1: pick a new target
         (set! target-x (+ 20 (modulo (world/hash) 280)))
         (set! target-y (+ 20 (modulo (world/hash) 200))))
       (motion/move-to p target-x target-y 2) ;; constraint 2: glide toward it
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'target target-x target-y 4 4)
       (paint-cell 'hero (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 12)))))
(big-bang glide-to-target)
```

`motion/move-to` is the built-in stop-when-arrived primitive.
Constraint 2 is expressed in a single verb call. Once the sprite is
within one step of the target, `motion/move-to` sets velocity to
zero automatically.

### 18. Enemy patrols between two walls

Enemy oscillates between two x-values, reversing direction each time
it hits a bound. Two constraints: reverse-at-left, reverse-at-right,
both checked every frame.

```scheme
(define (patrol)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((e (world/spawn 'guard 100 120))
        (left-edge 60) (right-edge 260))
    (entity/shape! e 'rect 12 12)
    (entity/set-vel! e 1.5 0)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (world/step)
       (let ((x (entity/x e))
             (vx (car (entity/vel e))))
         (cond
           ((and (<= x left-edge)  (< vx 0))   ;; constraint 1: left bound reached
            (entity/set-vel! e (- vx) 0))
           ((and (>= x right-edge) (> vx 0))   ;; constraint 2: right bound reached
            (entity/set-vel! e (- vx) 0))))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'guard (entity/x e) (entity/y e) 12 12)))))
(big-bang patrol)
```

Two symmetric constraints. When the guard is at or past the left
edge AND moving left, flip velocity. When at or past the right edge
AND moving right, flip. The AND-with-direction check prevents the
guard from getting stuck at an edge with velocity pushing it back
into the wall.

---

### The pattern: read the prompt, don't drift

Every one of these six games follows the same authoring shape:

1. **Name each constraint.** 'Move right' + 'stop at edge' = two
   constraints. Write them down before you pick verbs.
2. **Pick the verb for each constraint.** `entity/set-vel!` for
   'move.' `entity/x` compared to `right-edge` for 'stop when past
   x=N.' One verb per constraint when possible.
3. **Compose in `on-frame`.** The frame loop is where both
   constraints are checked every tick. Neither drifts because both
   are re-evaluated 60 times a second.
4. **Verify each constraint independently.** Temporarily comment out
   the stop-condition and confirm the sprite moves. Temporarily set
   the velocity to zero and confirm the stop-condition would fire.
   If each works alone, they work together.

If your code starts using verbs you didn't intend — `ai/wander`
instead of `entity/set-vel!` when the prompt said 'move right,' say
— that's DRIFT. Stop, re-read the prompt, restart. The verbs you
need are always the smallest verbs that name the constraint.

See book-of-composition Chapter 16 for the meta-pattern in more
detail. See book-of-scheme Appendix D for the 'move-until-condition'
pattern entry.")
